table-1286-709.pgTitle: List of Scheduled Monuments in Anglesey
table-1286-709.caption: Scheduled Monuments in Anglesey
data: Neolithic chambered tomb overlooking Trecastle Bay. Excavated in 1952-3 it is now consolidated, with lockable iron gates and a glass domed roof. Several internal stones have Neolithic pecked geometric rock art.
The burial mound developed over several phases, culmination in a 3m high Portal Stone creating a substantial entrance. The mound has now gone, leaving the internal stone structures.
Standing Stone 3m high between Y Werthyr and Bryn Llwyd farms. Early writings suggest there was a second upright and a long capstone, of which there is now no sign.
Two megalithic burial chambers with a 2m gap between. A single mound would once have covered them both, now disappeared without trace.
At some 4m high this stone slab is one of the tallest standing stones on Anglesey.
Three Bronze Age Standing Stones, each some 2m high, at the top of a low ridge.

Huge capstone supported by 8 side stones, all of locally occurring limestone. Described in 1781, excavated in 1909, it contained numerous Neolithic flints and pots, along with 15-30 human burials. Possible East, West and South alignment of stones suggest astronomical purposes
In woodland west of Plas Bodafaon, the stone is 1.3m high, of an unusual quartzite.
Enclosed Hut Group West of Mariandyrys
Hut Circle W of Buarth Cyttir
Hut Group S of Bwlch, Benllech
Penmon Deer Park Hut Groups & Terraces
A later prehistoric pentagonal enclosure, 49 yards (45m) across. It is a possible defended settlement and stands a few hundred metres south of Pen-y-Morwydd Barrow.
Prominent burial mound on a hill-top between Llanfechell and Bodewryd. It is metres (ft) across, and metres (ft) high, crossed by a modern wall. A footpath from Rhosbeirio crosses the mound.
Roughly rectangular walled enclosure. Within it a well defined roundhouse, 6m across with paved floor, had Roman pottery finds. There are also two large rectangular buildings.
Hut circle of 8m diameter with rubble-filled 1.3m thick walls, up to 0.8m high. Now in thick woodland, rectangular buildings alongside have also been recorded.

Circular hut and a nearby mound of discarded shellfish, with pottery and other items including half of a bronze ring. The hut had flooring of cobbles set in the earth, and a mortar stone set into the floor.
Enclosed Hut Circle Settlement at Capel Llochwydd
Coed Newydd Boiling Mounds & Smelting Hearth
Stone foundation walls of a group of Iron Age houses and workshops, surrounded by an enclosing wall.
A Roman-era hillfort on the summit of the Holyhead Mountain. Now mostly rubble, but its walls can still be made out, including a large stone rampart on the north and east sides.
Bivalate hillfort on an imposing hill top. Ramparts are now mostly ploughed out.
AN158 . Cadw SAM: AN158: Y Werthyr Hillfort
Civil War stone fortifications on a medieval motte
Early medieval religious foundation that was an Augustinian Priory by 1237
Thirteenth century llys, a court of the princes of Gwynedd, excavated in 1993
Windmill, Engine House, Precipitation Pits and Great Opencast
North Weir and Smoke Tower, Ynys Gorad Goch
Dyffryn Adda Copper Furnace and Precipitation Ponds
Kilns and Sublimation Chambers at Mona Mine, Mynydd Parys
The Stanley Embankment links Holyhead to Anglesey

data: 4 deaths — A tornado curved to the northeast and east as it passed through the south side of Hot Springs, The tornado damaged 200 homes, one of which was left in front of a train.
1 death — A tornado touched down in a small community, damaging or destroying 12 homes. Several tenant homes were also blown down miles (km) east of Greenland, killing a woman inside one of them.
A tornado destroyed many barns in the Sage area.
A tornado struck Pulaski Heights on the west side of Little Rock, unroofing homes in the area.

2+ deaths — A tornado injured 22 people and killed a man and his daughter as their home was destroyed miles (km) south of Cabot. Two other people were badly injured and may have died many weeks later.
1 death — A tornado destroyed homes and other structures on six farms.
A tornado reportedly destroyed homes and barns.
A tornado destroyed barns miles (km) from town.
4 deaths — A tornado transported bodies up to miles (km) from tenant homes which were destroyed. Three members of one family died.
1 death — One home was destroyed, killing a man who was thrown miles (km) from the foundation.
2 deaths — A tornado struck south of Stuttgart, killing two people each on different plantations.
4 deaths — A tornado hit three large farms, destroying 16 tenant homes and killing four people on one of the farms.
A tornado was sighted from a train as it destroyed small homes, barns, and a nearby school.
7 deaths — Seven people died in five different families as a tornado leveled their homes.

table-1286-216.caption: Research Themes at the Institute for Genomic Biology
data: Develops quantitative techniques for the description and study of natural phenomena on many levels, from single molecules to ecosystems.
Develops tools to efficiently and systematically control gene expression in eukaryotic cells, technology with potential applications in medicine, food crop improvement and biofuel production.
Business, Economics and Law of Genomic Biology (BioBEL)
Explores the economic and legal implications of novel genomics-related technologies and the development of industries around those technologies.
Builds the understanding of the molecular, cellular, and multicellular events that lead to cancer.
Examines how alterations in carbon uptake and release in organisms exposed to aspects of global climate change are mediated by gene networks.
Gene Networks in Neural and Developmental Biology (GNDP)

Investigates the conserved gene networks that may support commonalities in behavior across diverse animal species, and how differences in those networks contribute to behavioral differences between species.
Characterizes the functions and properties of microbial gene products and metabolites, in an effort to discover molecules with novel and useful chemical properties.
Investigates the properties of tissue growth, and develops technologies to replace or regenerate tissues or organs that have been affected by medical conditions.

Meanwhile, Fletch and Rita treat a young man claiming to be the reincarnation of an elderly woman's brother and, following her secret abortion, Tess returns to work where Fletch tells her that he loves her, even though she's decided that their relationship can't go on any further.

As a car comes to a halt in a busy road, a bus filled with passengers swerves, clips a central reserve and crashes on its side. While most passengers get clear, a young girl named Lucy is pulled to safety as another passenger runs. With the paramedics on the scene, the injured are rushed to the ED. When a wounded man stumbles into the hospital's reception looking for treatment, Charlie soon realises that he must have been involved in the bus crash. But why was he not treated at the scene and picked up by the paramedics? Meanwhile, Lily is told to work alongside Rita in order to improve her cold bedside manner. Elsewhere, Tom asks Sam to move in with him. Note: First appearance of Iain Dean (Michael Stevenson)

A teenage couple end up in a tussle when he discovers she is hiding pills, and when they are almost hit by a car she faints, requiring the paramedics to take them to Holby. The ED, as well as the girls boyfriend, try to find out what the pills are. The two elderly sisters who almost ran into the youngsters are also injured in the incident, but they seem more interested in the kitten they were taking to the vet - and when Fletch notices one of then struggling to remember her words, he questions whether the ladies should even be living together, especially when the son wants his mother to live with him and his family.
